  <text>
    <body>
      <pb n="1"/>
      <p>
        <add>ב"ה באלטרמארע יום א י"א שבט תר חלפ"ק צרור המור ואשכל הכופר \ חכם וסופר \ הנותן אמרי שפר
          ה"ה גרץ בגוברין בהר"ר יצחק המוכה אלעזר</add>
      </p>
      <pb n="2"/>
      <p>
        <addressee>Rev I. Leeser</addressee>
        <placeName>Walnut St 371</placeName>
      </p>
      <p rend="indent(1)">
        <placeName>
          <hi rend="underline">Philadelphia</hi>
        </placeName>
      </p>
      <pb n="3"/>
      <p><placeName>Baltimore</placeName>, the 11<hi rend="sup">th</hi> of</p>
      <p>
        <date>Shevat (December, 1848)</date>
      </p>
      <p><addressee>Isaac Leeser</addressee>:</p>
      <p rend="indent(1)">I should gladly reply to your last<lb/> letter and the question you ask me
        there—how do<lb/> *I like Zung? But the many troubles, physical<lb/> and spiritual which I
        am undergoing, leave<lb/> me little time to write. Just today, however<add>?</add><lb/> have
        a bit of time. And I would like to make<lb/> this one remark. I have read the work with
        a<lb/> great deal of effort. I say, “with effort” because<lb/> such works, in which the
        footnotes make up more<lb/> than the strength, wear one out. And what do<lb/> you think have
        I gained after all this effort?<lb/> Not a thing. Our German gentleman doctors
        un-<lb/>fortunately suffer, all of them, from a certain disease,<lb/> so take the holiest
        subject and drop them down<lb/> with Greek and Latin criticism into the lowest<lb/> depths.
        The introduce strange ideas where<lb/> there have no application and no foundation.<lb/>
        According to this work, the Bible is no more Bible<lb/> and everything built upon it is
        certainly worth-<lb/>less. God protect us against all these doctors,<lb/> whose medicine
        chest is full of poison.</p>
      <p rend="indent(1)">I was particularly amused in your<lb/> last occident, of <date>Rosh
            C<add>?</add>desh Tebet</date>, by a notice</p>
      <p>*The reference is probably to <persName>Leopold Zung's</persName> “Zur<lb/> Geschichte und
        Literatur,” published <date>1845</date>.</p>
      <pb n="4"/>
      <p>of the clergyman <persName>Pazinansky</persName>.</p>
      <p rend="indent(1)">(The rest of this doesn't seem to make any<lb/> sense. In order to
        understand it, one would<lb/> have to look up that particular number of the<lb/> Occident to
        see what this man is talking about.<lb/> In any event, the letter <sic>doesnt</sic> add
        any-<lb/>thing except to say that that particular notice<lb/> amused the writer).</p>
      <p rend="indent(1)">In general I have no news. When<lb/> your prayer book is ready you may
        send<lb/> me two dozen. Perhaps in time I can dis-<lb/>pose of them. Please have them
        bound.</p>
      <p rend="indent(1)">He who has mercy upon everyone,<lb/> may He cause truth to grow in our
        land<lb/> and remove the spirit of <add>?</add> and<lb/>
        <add>?</add> from us.</p>
      <p rend="indent(4)">Your friend,</p>
      <p rend="indent(4)">
        <persName role="author">Abraham Reis</persName>
      </p>
    </body>
